          "body": "The chapter's second movement (vv. 24-41) might appear to be an appendix, but it is essential to the narrator's purpose. The new settlers brought into Samaria by the Assyrian king (17:24) quickly replicate the problem they were meant to replace: they do not fear the LORD (17:25), they construct their own gods (17:29-31), and they settle into the pattern the narrator calls 'fearing the LORD while serving their own gods' (17:33). This is the chapter's most penetrating pastoral target. The settlers are not openly atheistic — they perform Yahweh-worship alongside their native religions. But the narrator's final word is unambiguous (17:34): 'to this day they do not fear the LORD.' Superficial religious acknowledgment of Yahweh — alongside prior and persistent allegiances — is not covenant faithfulness; it is a more sophisticated form of the same apostasy that brought Israel into exile. The phrase 'to this day' (17:23, 34, 41) makes the warning present-tense for every reader: the danger is not past history but current practice. Syncretism — adding Christ to prior loyalties rather than replacing them — is the precise error this chapter targets."
